english:
  title: A Preface to Send Off the Monk Unseol of Seolak
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The disciple Unseol of Seolak, successor to Naeong, descended from the mountain and came to the capital to pay his respects to our esteemed teacher Mogŭn. He requested that the Master give a name to his meditation hall. The Master named it the Hall of Basking in Warmth and even composed a commemorative inscription for him to take away. When Unseol brought this inscription to show me, he spoke thus: "I visited the house of Mogŭn and received both the naming of my hall and the inscription. Yet my body has no fixed dwelling—how can there be such a thing as a hall? To force a name upon it as a hall is merely to anchor it in the Way. I have served my teacher for twenty long years, and still I have not grasped even a glimpse of that Way. Now that my teacher has departed, I seek within my own heart and without in names and words. I wish to pose my questions to the enlightened ones throughout the land and gather the wisdom of scholars to sustain me on my further journey. Since I took my vows, my feet have never entered the city—how would I know such learned men? You are a disciple of Mogŭn. If Mogŭn does not reject me, surely you will not either. Therefore I make this request of you alone."

    I replied: "How difficult it is for the Way to be transmitted! Though countless beings gathered on Spirit Mountain heard the Buddha's teaching, the True Dharma Eye was passed only through Kāśyapa alone. Though three thousand disciples of the Apricot Platform heard the Way of our Master, only Yan Hui truly approached it. So difficult is the transmission of the Way! And this is thousands of years after the sages departed. In recent times in our Eastern lands, among Buddhist practitioners, only Naeong—the teacher of your teacher—inherited the lineage of Zhixong and Pingshan, returned eastward, and opened the gates for later students. At his passing, there appeared the extraordinary relics, confirming that he could indeed transmit what others could not. Even for those who studied long in his presence, how easy is it to glimpse the limits of his attainment?

    Yet the Way does not depart from form and substance—it is not the realm of vague obscurity and delusion. Neither does it become entangled in form and substance—it is not shallow and hasty compromise. Within, it is complete in my own heart; without, it manifests in all things. Abandon the heart, and there is no root, and the body cannot stand. Depart from the affairs of things, and it is incomplete, and function cannot operate. When body and function are complete, and inner and outer nourish each other equally—this is the learning of we Confucians. The Way of the Buddhists, though I do not fully comprehend it, does not depart from this heart. And this heart is vast as the void, without distinction between self and other, inner and outer. That your teacher seeks the Way both in the heart and in names is because he understands that inner and outer are not two separate truths. When you later question the enlightened ones, surely there will be resonance.
  footnotes:
    - Mogŭn (牧隱) refers to Paek Mun-bo (1338-1407), a major Neo-Confucian scholar of Koryŏ.
    - The Hall of Basking in Warmth (負暄堂) is a reference to a Daoist sage who sought warmth from the sun—suggesting a humble, natural way of life.
    - Spirit Mountain (靈山) refers to the place where Buddha delivered his teachings; the 'True Dharma Eye' (正法眼藏) represents the essential transmission of Buddhist truth.
    - Naeong (懶翁, 1320-1376) was a prominent Korean Buddhist monk; Zhixong (指空) and Pingshan (平山) were renowned Chan Buddhist masters.
    - This work combines Confucian and Buddhist philosophy, exploring how the Way transcends yet includes both the inner realm of mind and the outer realm of phenomena.
